## The Tip Vulnerability Rule

Every pear diamond has a pointed tip. That tip is the structural weak point. In the hierarchy of diamond shapes, the pear is second only to the marquise in tip fragility — a hard knock, a countertop, even a zipper can chip an exposed point.

In a **prong setting**, the tip sits in a single v-prong. It is visible, aesthetically clean, and classically elegant. But an unprotected pear tip accumulates micro-chips over years of daily wear. On a ring, this risk is high because hands contact surfaces constantly. On a **pendant**, the risk is lower — pendants swing freely and rarely impact hard surfaces directly. But it is not zero: the tip can hit clavicle bones, other necklaces, or the inside of a collar.

In a **bezel setting**, a rim of metal fully encircles the stone including the tip. The [James Allen Bezel Solitaire series](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/bezel-solitaire-pendant-necklace-with-025-ctw-pear-shaped-diamond-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-310934?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the [East-West Bezel Solitaire series](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/east-west-bezel-solitaire-pendant-necklace-with-025-ctw-pear-shaped-diamond-in-14k-white-gold-item-297496?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) fully protect the tip. For daily-wear pendants — pieces you put on in the morning and remove at night — the bezel is the correct default. The prong is for occasional wear or when maximum stone visibility matters more than durability.

---

## The Chain Length Illusion

Most buyers focus entirely on the pendant and treat the chain as an afterthought. This is a mistake that produces expensive regret. The chain length determines where the stone sits on the body, and that determines everything about how the pendant reads.

**16 inches** positions the pendant at the base of the throat. It reads formal, elegant, and high-fashion. It pairs best with V-necklines and open collars where the stone can be seen clearly. It photographs exceptionally well.

**18 inches** is the most versatile length — the stone sits at the top of the sternum, works with most necklines, and reads appropriately for both daytime and evening wear.

**20 inches** drops the pendant to mid-chest or bust. It reads casual and layering-friendly but the stone gets partially obscured by clothing in many contexts. A 1 ct pear at 20" reads smaller than the same stone at 16" because viewing distance increases and neckline coverage reduces visibility.

The [1 ct lab Point Up pendant at $930](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/point-up-pear-cut-lab-grown-diamond-solitaire-pendant-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-251324?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at 16" looks like a statement piece. The same pendant at 20" reads as casual fine jewelry. Buy the chain length that matches the occasion profile you are building for.

