## Bezel vs Prong: The Pendant Setting Decision

The Tip Vulnerability Rule frames this clearly, but the full comparison goes further.

**Bezel (JA Bezel series, EW Bezel series):** Metal rim encloses the full perimeter of the stone including the tip. Protects against chipping. Creates a more modern, architectural look. Adds metal weight to the setting, which can slightly reduce face-up stone visibility at the edges. Best for daily wear, active lifestyles, and buyers prioritizing longevity.

**Prong (Point Up solitaire series):** Minimal metal contacts the stone — typically 4–6 prongs with a v-prong at the tip. Maximum stone visibility. Classic, bridal-adjacent aesthetic. The tip is exposed. Best for occasional wear, formal jewelry wardrobes, and buyers who prioritize visual impact over durability.

For a pear pendant — specifically because pendants swing freely and the tip can contact the wearer — the bezel is the practical recommendation for daily use. The [JA Bezel Natural 0.25 ct at $892](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/bezel-solitaire-pendant-necklace-with-025-ctw-pear-shaped-diamond-in-14k-yellow-gold-by-james-allen-item-310934?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the entry-level daily-wear natural pendant. The [Point Up Lab 1 ct at $930](https://www.bluenile.com/jewelry/necklaces/point-up-pear-cut-lab-grown-diamond-solitaire-pendant-in-14k-yellow-gold-1-ct-tw-f-g-vs2-si1-item-251324?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the prong alternative for buyers who prioritize size and visibility over full tip protection.

